<TITLE> Rising star Miliband set for key foreign post </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 June 28 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - British Prime Minister Gordon Brown will name David Miliband, 41, as new foreign minister on Thursday in a government shakeup designed to draw a line under a decade of Tony Blair's rule, according to political sources. Rising star Miliband is seen as a future Labour Party leader and only recently ended speculation that he might run against Brown in the contest to succeed Blair as prime minister. Miliband was reportedly sceptical about Blair's decision to go to war in Iraq and, according to media reports, voiced his dismay in cabinet at the former prime minister's reluctance to call for an immediate ceasefire in last year's Lebanon war. Here are some details about Miliband: David Miliband, born in July 1965, was educated at Haverstock Comprehensive School in London. He graduated in philosophy, politics and economics from Corpus Christi College, Oxford University, and completed a masters degree in political science at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, where he was a Kennedy Scholar. From 1989 to 1994 he was Research Fellow at the Institute for Policy Research and from 1992 to 1994 Secretary of the Commission on Social Justice, becoming part of Blair's inner circle since before Labour came to power in 1997. He was elected as Member of Parliament in the safe seat of South Shields in 2001, within a year becoming a middle-rank minister after being handed the school standards brief and in 2004 he was made Cabinet Office minister. He joined the Cabinet in 2005 as Minister of Communities and Local Government, serving in former Deputy Prime Minister John Prescott's department. In May 2006, he moved to the Department of Environment, Farming and Rural Affairs where he replaced Margaret Beckett when she moved to become Foreign Secretary. He is married to Louise Shackelton, a violinist for the London Symphony Orchestra. They have one chi
